{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/depression-in-children/diagnosis/diagnosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f076b5d2-7785-5b8a-8164-72a53569465d","slug":"diagnosis","fullItemName":"Diagnosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9dcd1997-6b39-42f2-a8fb-fd31dedc86ff --><h2>How should I make a diagnosis of depression in a child or young person?</h2><!-- end field 9dcd1997-6b39-42f2-a8fb-fd31dedc86ff -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item c7423034-65a4-453e-a9ec-4fa12680346a --><!-- begin field f1bc62eb-18d6-4145-b507-797990b4545c --><p><strong>Healthcare professionals involved in the assessment of a child (aged 5–11 years) or young person (aged 12–18 years) with depression should be aware of the <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/depression-in-children/diagnosis/general-principles-of-care/\">general principles of care</a> for children and young people with depression.</strong></p><p><strong>Following an <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/depression-in-children/diagnosis/assessment/\">assessment</a> of the child or young person:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>D</strong><strong>iagnose:</strong><ul><li><strong>Mild depression </strong>if there is persistent sadness or low mood (or irritability) with either anhedonia or tiredness, plus 2<em> </em>associated symptoms (4 symptoms in total). Associated symptoms are:<ul><li>Reduced concentration and attention.</li><li>Reduced self-esteem and self-confidence.</li><li>Ideas of guilt and unworthiness.</li><li>Bleak and pessimistic views of the future.</li><li>Ideas or acts of self-harm or suicide.</li><li>Disturbed sleep.</li><li>Diminished appetite.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Moderate depression</strong> if there is persistent sadness or low mood (or irritability) with either anhedonia or tiredness, plus 3 or 4 associated symptoms (5–6 symptoms in total).</li><li><strong>Severe depression</strong> if there is persistent sadness or low mood (or irritability), anhedonia, and tiredness, plus 4 or more<em> </em>associated symptoms (7 or more symptoms in total).</li></ul></li><li><strong>Be aware that:</strong><ul><li>The mood change must last throughout the waking hours (although some may improve gradually through the day, only to return to feeling depressed on waking), and both the mood change and concurrent symptoms must persist for at least 2 weeks.</li><li>Depression should only be diagnosed when the symptoms and signs lead to significant personal suffering and are accompanied by observable social impairment, although social impairment may be less obvious in children and young people with mild depression.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field f1bc62eb-18d6-4145-b507-797990b4545c --><!-- end item c7423034-65a4-453e-a9ec-4fa12680346a -->","topic":{"id":"101ea2c8-5f55-5359-aeda-5b20ef97f370","topicId":"088b8823-67f3-4e08-81f1-8778bd49b12e","topicName":"Depression in children","slug":"depression-in-children","lastRevised":"Last revised in  August 2020","chapters":[{"id":"f64dd2b3-170d-5d9b-aecb-1a2978ecb4e1","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e6e1d043-84eb-5268-9881-e9206a00a233","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5e95ca6c-8f50-5b31-b155-739311de5b50","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"f3f0affc-e4a2-56b0-b121-2d69b1330cca","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"3f5587ad-b1bc-595c-b884-a355ab80031e","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"bca87a5c-ec4c-59fd-8119-690fc138098f","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"d5cd25b2-ada4-5e22-ab78-d6e7ccafcc1b","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"bccddba5-ed7c-5703-8bc4-1b28d9f71a65","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"